## Non-negotiable conventions

### Async / cancellation
- Every I/O method must be `async Task<T>`, never sync over async
- `CancellationToken ct = default` on every public async method signature
- Pass `ct` through ‚Äî never discard it

### HttpClient
- Never `new HttpClient()` inside a method body
- Always inject via `IHttpClientFactory` or as a constructor dependency
- Dispose correctly ‚Äî prefer `using var` at the call site if creating locally

### Dependency injection
- Register everything in `Program.cs` or a dedicated `ServiceCollectionExtensions`
- Primary constructor injection: `public sealed class Foo(IBar bar)` ‚Äî preferred over field assignment
- No service locator pattern (`IServiceProvider` injection is a smell)

### Error handling
- Throw specific exceptions (`InvalidOperationException`, `ArgumentException`, etc.)
- Only catch `Exception` at application boundary (middleware, top-level handler)
- Never swallow exceptions silently

### Logging
- `ILogger<T>` always ‚Äî never `Console.WriteLine` in production code
- Structured templates: `logger.LogInformation("Processing {Count} items", count)`
- Never string interpolation in log calls

## Style

- `var` when type is obvious from right-hand side; explicit type otherwise
- File-scoped namespaces: `namespace Foo.Bar;`
- No `#region` blocks
- Records for DTOs: `public record Foo(string Bar, int Baz);`
- Collection expressions: `List<int> x = [1, 2, 3];`

## Patterns in this codebase

### Agent pattern
Agents implement `IAgent`. Route via `CanHandle(ctx)`. Run concurrently with `Task.WhenAll`.
Never add orchestration logic inside an agent.

### Prompt templates
Prompts live in `Prompts/*.txt`. Load via `IPromptLoader`, never hardcode in C#.
Substitution slots use `{{VARIABLE_NAME}}` convention.

## What Cursor should never suggest

- `.Result` or `.Wait()` ‚Äî always async
- `new HttpClient()` inline
- `catch (Exception ex) { }` with empty body
- Hardcoded connection strings or API keys
- `Thread.Sleep` ‚Äî use `await Task.Delay`
